<p align="center"><font color="#0E024D" face="Arial"><strong>PLAYER SUBMITTED STRATEGY</strong></font></p>
<div align="center"><center>

  <div align="center"><center><table border="0" width="90%">
    <tr>
      <td>
      <center><font face="Arial"><strong><b><font color="#800000">MEDITATE WHILE KITING</b></font> - <small>Deara Dragonclaw, Rodcet Nife</small></strong></font><font face="Arial"></center>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td>
    <small><hr size="1" color="#C0C0C0"><P>
    Have you ever noticed while meditating that your mana actually increases in small jumps?  You can use this to your advantage while kiting.  The basic strategy is to run for 4 or 5 seconds, then sit down and meditate during the "tick" that increases your mana.  Immediately get back up and run again!  I found that I could kite Avocets that were yellow and low red and still have lots of mana left over at the end.<p>My basic strategy was as follows:  I would have my best DD and DoT memorized, along with my best Shield of XXX (Barbs or Brambles), best heal spell, gate (for when it doesn't work or SOW goes away at exactly the wrong time!), SOW and Snare.  I would generally have Spirit of Cheetah memorized as an emergency escape valve if I needed it but you don't really need it.  Make sure you have Wolfform or SOW, Skin like Steel and XXXcoat cast on yourself before starting.<p>I would always start by casting Snare; some like to start with a DoT, but to be able to meditate while kiting, you need the snare on the MoB.  If snare fails, run till you are far enough ahead to cast again.  Repeat until Snare sticks.  Now, I would cast my best DoT, and if you want your best DD as well.  Now, run for a few seconds to get ahead and sit and meditate.  Watch your mana bar carefully and at the first sign of movement immediately get up and run.  Run for a count of 4 then sit and meditate till the "tick".  Do this while you time your DoTs and snare.  Reapply them as needed or burn with your DD.  I would repeat this series of run, med, cast if needed, till the avocet was almost dead, then I would turn and DD and/or melee to finish it off.<p>This strategy will work as soon as you get SOW at level 14.  Just modify the spells based on what you have at that time.  Of course, you need to be kiting in an area where you won't pick up "company."  I used this on Crag Spiders in East Karana when I was younger and I can use this method to solo Hill Giants at level 34, even with the nerfed DoTs (I solo'd a Sand Giant at 29 before the DoT nerf, but never tried it again until 34).<p>This strategy takes a little practice, but it is well worth it! We've all been in the situation where you have a MoB down to almost no HP, but you are OOM and can't stand toe to toe for melee.  Using this method, you can recover enough mana to finish off the target rather than having to zone and lose the XP from all your hard work.  The key though is keeping that Snare refreshed!<p>Good luck and happy hunting!<p>Deara Dragonclaw<br>Legion of Avatar<br>Rodcet Nife
    </small></font></p>
    <p><small><font face="Arial">&nbsp;</font></small></td>
  </tr>
